# Security Conventions

## Open redirects
Never pass a user-supplied value directly to `NextResponse.redirect()` or `redirect()`.
Always validate that redirect targets are safe relative paths:

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — attacker can supply ?next=https://evil.com
const next = searchParams.get("next") ?? "/";
return NextResponse.redirect(new URL(next, request.url));

// ✅ GOOD
function safeRelativePath(next: string | null): string {
  if (next && /^\/(?!\/)/.test(next)) return next;
  return "/";
}
```

## FormData — never cast to string
See `server-actions` rule. `formData.get()` returns `File | string | null`.

## Supabase
- **Never** use `getSession()` server-side — it reads from the cookie without re-validating. Always use `getUser()` which hits the Supabase Auth server.
- **Never** expose `SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY` in client components or `NEXT_PUBLIC_` vars. It bypasses Row-Level Security entirely.
- Use `@/lib/supabase/server` in all server contexts; `@/lib/supabase/browser` only in Client Components.

## Password reset flow
Require **both** a valid session **and** a short-lived `HttpOnly` recovery cookie to access `/reset-password`. The cookie is set in `/auth/confirm` only when `type === "recovery"` and is cleared after a successful password update. This prevents any logged-in user reaching the reset form outside the email flow.

## Security headers
All HTTP security headers are configured in `next.config.ts` and applied globally.
Do not remove or weaken: `X-Frame-Options`, `X-Content-Type-Options`, `Strict-Transport-Security`, `Referrer-Policy`, `Permissions-Policy`.

## Row-Level Security
Every Supabase table must have RLS enabled. The anon key is public and can read any table without RLS.
